{
  "winner": "tie",
  "candidate_a_score": 75,
  "candidate_b_score": 75,
  "rationale": "Both candidates submitted identical patches. They correctly removed the Express backend, updated the dev script, cleaned up dependencies, added basic vercel.json rewrites, and switched logo fetching to images.weserv.nl. However, both lack the reference's additional QR code CORS handling (crossOrigin attribute, imageOptions), omit the URL protocol stripping and n=-1 parameter for the proxy, fail to remove the unused downloadQR/jsPDF code, and omit the version field in vercel.json."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 100,
  "candidate_b_score": 98,
  "rationale": "Both candidates correctly remove the custom McpController, update McpDocController to extend McpServerController from package:finch/mcp.dart, bump finch to 1.3.0, and drop mcp_models. Candidate A matches the reference exactly, including import order and whitespace preservation. Candidate B introduces minor unrelated churn by reversing the import order and removing an extra blank line in pubspec.yaml, making it slightly less aligned with the reference."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 38,
  "candidate_b_score": 62,
  "rationale": "Candidate B correctly implements the sequential x-axis (simulation replicate index) as required, matching the reference structure and function signatures, but has broken true-value annotations (all overlapping at x=0.5) and omits data sorting/subsetting. Candidate A fundamentally violates the core requirement by plotting against true_val_col instead of a sequential x-axis, which misrepresents the requested plot, though it spaces annotations horizontally. Both candidates miss the sorting and column-subsetting logic present in the reference."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 88,
  "candidate_b_score": 74,
  "rationale": "Candidate_a aligns better with the reference: it uses proper client-side navigation in ProtectedRoute (Navigate), wraps the courses page with Navbar/Footer, keeps scroll concerns modular, and provides a complete show-all/toggle experience. Candidate_b regresses by using window.location.href for auth redirects (full reload, no state preservation), omits layout wrappers on the courses page, and inlines scroll components in App.jsx."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 70,
  "candidate_b_score": 60,
  "rationale": "Candidate A produces valid Tailwind CSS (border-l-[3px]) and wires the hidden file input to an onUpload handler, preserving attachment functionality. Its main weaknesses are exposing the Internal comment tab unconditionally (a logic/security regression) and accessing ticket metadata without .name. Candidate B correctly gates the Internal tab and uses .name accessors, but breaks file upload with an empty onChange handler and uses an invalid Tailwind class (border-l-3), causing clear functional and visual defects."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 25,
  "candidate_b_score": 75,
  "rationale": "Candidate B implements the required server-side MP4 validation (checking for HTML signatures and ftyp) and browser fallback on move failure, broadly aligning with the reference. Candidate A contains critical correctness issues: it uses the undefined os.ReadFull function, performs a case-sensitive extension check with dead code (len(header) < 12 is always false for a fixed 12-byte slice), and only falls back when the server explicitly returns success: false rather than on any move failure."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 30,
  "candidate_b_score": 50,
  "rationale": "Both candidates failed to include the required Trilha.jsx learning-path data, which is a major completeness gap. However, Candidate B provided clean, focused changes to Dashboard and Questionario with minimal unrelated churn, correct point-based scoring, and proper currentTarget hover effects aligned with the reference. Candidate A introduced extensive unrelated Dashboard restyling, altered UX text and colors, removed the user-loading guard (if (!usuario) return null), and used e.target instead of e.currentTarget for hover states, making it less correct and less aligned."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 88,
  "candidate_b_score": 18,
  "rationale": "Candidate A fully implements SSE streaming with keepalive, updates all six client pages to use a shared consumer, and correctly enhances analyzeDraft with higher token limits, compact citations, bracket-repair, and fallback handling. It diverges modestly from the reference in SSE field formatting and client API signature but remains complete and correct. Candidate B only updates one client page, severely breaks analyzeDraft with a wrong signature, corrupted syntax, and deleted logic, regresses server error handling, and removes the maxDuration export."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 30,
  "candidate_b_score": 65,
  "rationale": "Candidate_a completely omits the Wig.tsx SA Lead Measures drilldown, failing half the task. Candidate_b implements both required components but deviates from the reference in several ways, including on-demand fetching instead of pre-fetching people data, schema field mismatches (intro_date vs class_date), missing disabled-button behavior for zero counts, and omitting friend_name in pack subtitles. Nonetheless, candidate_b is substantially more complete and functional."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 75,
  "candidate_b_score": 25,
  "rationale": "Candidate A correctly wires conditional physical modifier events around mapped keycodes and routes code==0 keys through onKey when modifiers are active, matching the task and reference despite minor unrelated churn. Candidate B introduces a fatal early return that bypasses all keycode mapping in handleKey, sending raw unmapped app codes for modified keys and breaking both special keys and character handling."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 20,
  "candidate_b_score": 40,
  "rationale": "Candidate A only fixes the member page lint issue while completely omitting the core admin features, backend API, and trend chart. Candidate B implements the energy-adjust backend API, admin dialogs, and member page fix, but places the member-management UI in the wrong file (platform admin instead of main admin), introduces a scope bug by using member-adjustment state inside ProvidersPage, and uses unsafe body-based admin authentication rather than proper request auth. It also only adds minimal empty-state handling to the trend chart. Despite significant correctness and alignment issues, Candidate B covers more requirements than A."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 45,
  "candidate_b_score": 80,
  "rationale": "Candidate A implements the correct algorithmic logic but uses exported field casing `row.Kind` instead of the unexported `row.kind` shown in the reference, which would cause a compile error. Candidate B uses the correct field names and compiles. While B collapses the worker-then-agent fallback into a single OR pass (relying on row ordering rather than explicitly preferring workers) and adds a minor early-return that skips the empty-dashboard flash edge case, it functionally satisfies the requirements and aligns far better with the reference direction."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 82,
  "candidate_b_score": 65,
  "rationale": "Candidate A implements all 10 components with correct props and functional fidelity to the reference. Its table-responsive accepts headers, form-select handles associative arrays, and breadcrumb uses the expected item structure. The exam layout covers anti-cheat and timer requirements, though it includes inappropriate non-English text and slightly deviates in flash-message placement. Candidate B misses critical functionality: table-responsive omits the headers prop entirely (a core requirement), form-select breaks on standard associative option arrays, and its breadcrumb demo shows broken usage. While B's exam anti-cheat is slightly more robust and its alert wrappers are DRYer, the component bugs and extraneous demo churn make it less correct and complete."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 30,
  "candidate_b_score": 75,
  "rationale": "Candidate A fatally early-returns only the debug panel when import.meta.env.DEV is true, completely suppressing the overlap banner during development and breaking the component's core functionality. Candidate B satisfies all major requirements—panel renders in DEV only, is collapsible, shows pair details, highlights matches, and appears regardless of overlap state—but deviates from the reference by adding a redundant separate query instead of extending the existing one, and incorrectly computes 'mine' and 'theirs' counts as unique city names rather than total itinerary lengths."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 45,
  "candidate_b_score": 72,
  "rationale": "Candidate B is architecturally sound with valid Prisma schema and proper server components, but loses points for nested forms in the detail page (breaking delete) and omitting date handling in create/update actions. Candidate A fatally imports Prisma and auth into a client component (list page), causing a build/runtime failure and potential credential exposure, and introduces a Prisma schema syntax error with an extra closing brace. While A's actions are more complete, the critical client-side Prisma misuse makes it far less correct."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 72,
  "candidate_b_score": 58,
  "rationale": "Candidate A correctly preserves per-service cookie grouping for cobalt.json and returns Netscape metadata (domain, secure, expiry) matching the reference intent, despite missing tests, lacking errors='replace', and setting valid_json=True for missing cobalt files. Candidate B violates the explicit per-service requirement by flattening all cobalt cookie names into a single global list, and its Netscape response omits metadata fields, making it less correct and aligned. Both omitted tests and used broad exception handling."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 70,
  "candidate_b_score": 55,
  "rationale": "Candidate A correctly switches to the Vite dev server, removes the custom backend and unused dependencies, adds the Vercel SPA routing config, updates the logo proxy to the public service, and includes the required useEffect cleanup for the QR container. Candidate B matches the infrastructure and proxy changes but omits the useEffect cleanup entirely. Both candidates miss adding the imageOptions block to qrCode.update and do not remove the legacy downloadQR function as shown in the reference."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 78,
  "candidate_b_score": 22,
  "rationale": "Candidate A delivers all required components—cc-explore/build/continue wrappers, session-start and end-conversation skills, statusline script, configure.sh, cc-doctor, and .gitignore updates—so it is functionally complete. However, it deviates from the reference in several details: the .gitignore exception path for canonical/CLAUDE.md is incorrect (uses 'canonical/CLAUDE.md' instead of the full repo-relative path), the statusline uses fragile grep/sed rather than jq to parse JSON, it introduces an extra canonical/settings-sandbox.json not present in the reference, and it writes .cc-mode to $HOME in build mode rather than the repo root. Candidate B provides only .gitignore and configure.sh; while those two files are reasonably aligned with the reference, the patch completely omits the shell functions, skills, statusline command, and doctor script, making it severely incomplete."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 75,
  "candidate_b_score": 90,
  "rationale": "Candidate B more closely matches the reference direction by fully stripping unused plan fields and rendering a uniform, static 'Coming soon' placeholder on every card. Candidate A retains unnecessary conditional CTA styling and dead data properties (emails, campaigns), introducing unrelated churn and deviating from the intended clean, static placeholder."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 70,
  "candidate_b_score": 35,
  "rationale": "Candidate A fulfills all core requirements: updated URLs, expanded challenge/login detection, cookie restoration with fallback, and cookie sync after both search and re-login. Its parallel solver is algorithmically correct but has a channel-management flaw that risks deadlock under high load. Candidate B suffers from a compile-breaking undefined method call (syncCookieToUser), completely omits post-re-login cookie synchronization, and its parallel solver incorrectly breaks each worker after finding a single hash, causing it to fail multi-target challenges."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 90,
  "candidate_b_score": 84,
  "rationale": "Both candidates correctly implement the core fix—scanning all signature occurrences, validating dwStrucVersion HIWORD==1, and rejecting majors >99. However, both lack the post-match bounds check present in the reference (Candidate A has a flawed pre-check; Candidate B has none), leaving a potential RangeError if the signature appears near the end of the buffer. Candidate A additionally fails to reject major==0, though this is harmless because the caller treats 0 as a non-match. Candidate B introduces unrelated comment churn in pickVendoredPythonDir and uses a slightly less consistent cleanup pattern. Candidate A’s test organization with helper functions is cleaner and closer to the existing file style, giving it a narrow edge."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 30,
  "candidate_b_score": 55,
  "rationale": "Candidate B covers all major requirements including the installed diagnostics script, package-tree comparison, and Codex hook status, whereas Candidate A omits the doctor script entirely and has incorrect marketplace logic. Both lack shared helpers and tests, but Candidate B is more complete and aligned with the task."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 88,
  "candidate_b_score": 58,
  "rationale": "Candidate A implements all required logic changes—including the critical Mask.apply empty-input handling—and adds tests in the target file, closely matching the reference scope. Candidate B omits the Mask.apply logic change, duplicates tests across an unnecessary new file, and introduces unrelated build.zig churn."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 68,
  "candidate_b_score": 82,
  "rationale": "Candidate_b correctly implements the email verification flow while preserving existing HTTP semantics (404 for NotFoundError, 400 for BadRequestError/EMAIL_NOT_VERIFIED). Candidate_a incorrectly changes NotFoundError to 400 status and uses plain Error objects instead of the project's error classes. Both candidates have minor deviations from the reference (e.g., Resend require pattern), but candidate_b is more correct and complete overall."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 82,
  "candidate_b_score": 70,
  "rationale": "Candidate A more faithfully aligns with the reference implementation: it updates homepage metadata, provides accurate comparison tables (e.g., correct 'No signup' for MarkLiveEdit), and delivers comprehensive guide/homepage content with proper JSON-LD schemas. Candidate B introduces factual inaccuracies in comparison pages (wrong signup claim for MarkLiveEdit, incorrect Typora cloud-sync rows), omits homepage metadata updates entirely, uses suboptimal <a> tags for internal navigation, and deviates from the reference with an unnecessary layout title-template change."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 48,
  "candidate_b_score": 38,
  "rationale": "Candidate A implements a partial but non-crashing escort-only routing flow, though it misses HUD labels, robbery support, post-arrival confirmation wiring, and safety checks for hull/system. Candidate B covers more surface (HUD localization, hull/system validation, both escort and rob) but introduces a critical runtime crash by reading `autopilot.pendingAction` immediately after `autopilot = undefined` in the arrival block, and miswires the interact handler to check the cleared autopilot state rather than the pending interaction state, making the confirmation flow completely broken."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 35,
  "candidate_b_score": 65,
  "rationale": "Candidate B addresses both core requirements—persisting course deletions via an API call and redesigning the ReplaceCourseModal candidate cards—whereas Candidate A entirely omits the critical modify-path-client deletion fix. Although Candidate B incorrectly imports deleteCourseFromPath from a newly created stub module instead of @/lib/api/rag, uses optimistic UI updates that deviate from the reference’s API-first flow, and introduces minor layout and formatting churn (e.g., 'Gratis' label, non-flex-1 link button, merged stats row), it is substantially more complete. Candidate A’s failure to handle the primary deletion flow, combined with unrelated import and handler churn in ReplaceCourseModal and an unsafe onDeleted() invocation on API failure, results in a significantly lower score."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 55,
  "candidate_b_score": 25,
  "rationale": "Candidate A creates a well-structured, mostly correct utility module with proper JSDocs and accurate primary regexes (INPUT_REQUIRED, DINPUT, and legacy placeholders), but completely omits integrating it into existing files. Candidate B attempts integration in SharedTeamChat.vue, yet introduces critical regressions: its INPUT_REQUIRED_REGEX is malformed (missing a closing bracket) and its LEGACY_RAW_TOKEN_REGEX is incorrect, which would break pattern detection and cleanup. An incomplete but safe module is preferable to a partially integrated but buggy one."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 84,
  "candidate_b_score": 66,
  "rationale": "Candidate A aligns closely with the reference architecture: it uses the required /user and /task route paths, preserves userID naming conventions, uses POST for refreshList with a JSON body, and employs module scripts. It correctly implements bcrypt hashing, parameterized queries, localStorage session management, and complete task CRUD with specific error messages. It loses points for heavy HTML restructuring churn, omitting package.json dependency updates for cors/bcrypt, and deviating from the reference date-input schema. Candidate B critically deviates from the specified API contract by retaining /users routes instead of /user, using id instead of userID throughout, switching refreshList to a GET request with query parameters, and introducing destructive SQL (DROP DATABASE IF EXISTS). It also includes significant unrelated churn (complete CSS rewrite, added isCompleted column, weakened NOT NULL constraints) and uses non-module scripts contrary to the reference direction."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 25,
  "candidate_b_score": 55,
  "rationale": "Candidate B aligns more closely with the reference architecture: the bible tree lives in the NavRail, the detail views replace placeholders as intended, and it extends the existing custom CSS rather than introducing an incompatible utility framework. However, Candidate B loses points for missing store state (activeCharacterId/setActiveCharacterId), a data integrity bug with malformed node IDs (e.g., ' continuity' vs 'continuity'), and sparse content seeding. Candidate A is penalized heavily for placing the tree inside the Bible view instead of the NavRail, using nonexistent Tailwind classes, importing the wrong store hook (useStore), and relying on missing store actions (toggleExpandedNode), resulting in multiple runtime defects and poor alignment with the target direction."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 10,
  "candidate_b_score": 25,
  "rationale": "Candidate B registers the migration, includes operational indexes for claiming and dead-letter listing, and provides a richer schema closer to the reference (e.g., signal_count, chain_depth, JSON ancestry). Candidate A is an unregistered, partial SQL file with weaker indexes and no integration. Both lack the required Rust DB/service layers and tests, but B is materially more complete and better aligned."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 55,
  "candidate_b_score": 25,
  "rationale": "Candidate A implements the core Rust from_lattice logic with in-plane Minkowski reduction and adds the required Python tests, but it misses critical Python integration pieces (lib.rs registration, __init__.py re-export, .pyi stubs) and contains a binding bug (calls PyLayerLattice::from_basis which does not exist). Candidate B registers the Python export and lib.rs class, but its PyLayerGroup constructor ignores the basis parameter entirely—skipping the required Minkowski-reduction path—and it omits tests and all core Rust changes for from_lattice, making it largely incomplete."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 95,
  "candidate_b_score": 88,
  "rationale": "Candidate A more closely follows the reference's simplification in SellPosController by removing the legacy erp_tx_ids accumulation and using erp_count directly, matching the target direction. Both candidates correctly switch to transaction-level SUM(total_before_tax) and update the blades, but Candidate B retains the old tx_ids pattern and erp_tx_count key, adding unnecessary churn and deviating from the reference's cleaner aggregation. Candidate A removes the explanatory text block in recent_feed entirely while Candidate B rewords it, but the controller alignment is the more significant differentiator."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 50,
  "candidate_b_score": 40,
  "rationale": "Candidate A attempts the full scope required by the task: a complete template redesign with panel-based tabs, comprehensive data-i18n coverage on labels/tabs/buttons, backend translation keys, new CSS/JS assets, and a translated test-email subject. Its main defects are missing i18n.js wiring and critical JavaScript syntax errors (missing commas in locale objects), which would prevent frontend translations from loading. Candidate B correctly wires i18n.js and produces syntactically valid JS locales, but it leaves the template in the old Bootstrap-tab structure, fails to apply the new CSS classes it creates, and adds data-i18n to only a handful of elements—missing the core redesign and most form-label translations. Because the task centers on a full-page i18n overhaul with a fresh panel-based layout, Candidate A’s broader structural attempt is more aligned with the reference direction despite its executable JavaScript flaws."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 35,
  "candidate_b_score": 0,
  "rationale": "Candidate A correctly captures the core fix—holding the live_state lock across tokio::spawn and the Running assignment to close the race—but introduces a syntax error (stray closing brace) and holds the lock longer than necessary by omitting the reference's limiting scope block. Candidate B is empty and fails the task entirely."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 80,
  "candidate_b_score": 38,
  "rationale": "Candidate A correctly implements the dynamic instanced-mesh grass ecosystem: propagation with neighbor clearance, slow regrowth, grazing death and slot recycling, seed-queue draining, and a toggleable stats overlay with rolling 60-second biomass delta and elapsed time. It also adds the required Vite polling config. It deviates modestly by inlining the overlay and keeping unused legacy SeededPlantMesh code, but the core behavior is complete and correct. Candidate B suffers from critical functional bugs: seeding is entirely broken because Ground.tsx never invokes the seed handler and App.tsx does not pass it; the biomass-delta computation nonsensically compares biomass values against elapsed time; and it introduces breaking API changes (altered BisonSpawn shape, removed audio, changed App to a named export) alongside heavy unrelated UI churn. These failures make Candidate B incomplete and unreliable."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 50,
  "candidate_b_score": 35,
  "rationale": "Candidate A covers more surface area: it adds governance IPC handlers, updates GitHubIssueCard types, implements per-repo concurrency gating (via dispatch-queue), and posts retry/failure comments. However, its retry logic is broken—failed issues are skipped on subsequent drive cycles and never re-attempted, violating the core backoff requirement. Candidate B correctly implements the retry kickoff loop (Pass 1) and uses numeric timestamps, but it misses all UI/renderer changes, omits IPC wiring, fails to update GitHubIssueCard types, destructively overwrites the existing governance-rules.json (dropping rules), and queries the wrong module (flight-board instead of dispatch-queue) for active task counts. Candidate A is closer to the reference in file scope and safer overall, despite its critical retry-scheduling bug."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 30,
  "candidate_b_score": 15,
  "rationale": "Candidate A provides a more complete implementation that aligns with the reference structure: it registers the algorithm, adds tests and static assets, and attempts to handle non-standard signatures and raw r||s encoding. However, it suffers from critical bugs including a severe truncation error (BigInt.toUnsigned(32) instead of byte-length handling), class name conflicts with pointycastle imports, and fragile manual ASN.1 parsing. Candidate B is weaker due to more fundamental design flaws: it double-hashes the message (passing a SHA-256 digest into an ECDSASigner that already hashes), relies on non-existent APIs (PEMParser), has a test scope/syntax error, and incorrectly treats raw signature components as ASN.1 integers in _bytesToBigInt. While both candidates are buggy, Candidate A’s verification path and test structure are closer to the target direction, making it the less incorrect solution."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 40,
  "candidate_b_score": 20,
  "rationale": "Candidate A preserves the original API request/response contracts and output formats for most routes it touches (agent-reaction, field-reword, pedestrian-chat) and consistently uses shared OpenAI helper imports. However, it incorrectly rewrites core business logic in companyBrief and sceneResponse, misses several required files (brief-chat, pedestrian-interview, agency-demo route, README, openaiResponses.ts, openaiManagedAgents.ts), and uses inconsistent environment variable names. Candidate B touches more files but introduces breaking API changes across almost every route, hardcodes responses in pedestrian-interview, strips budget tracking and error handling, and uses direct fetches instead of shared helpers, making it a destructive migration that fails the requirement of maintaining existing functionality."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 60,
  "candidate_b_score": 40,
  "rationale": "Candidate A implements mathematically correct max-drawdown (exp(cumsum) equity curve) and sound paired-pairs bootstrap mechanics, but misses joint block-length selection for Calmar/PF and mishandles a few edge-case sentinels. Candidate B fatally miscomputes the equity curve in max_drawdown_fraction by using raw cumsum instead of exp(cumsum), which breaks Calmar ratio correctness, and lacks early degenerate-input sentinels. Both have minor parameter-name and validation mismatches, but Candidate A's core primitives are sound where Candidate B's are not."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_b",
  "candidate_a_score": 25,
  "candidate_b_score": 72,
  "rationale": "Candidate A only partially strips tray code and incorrectly removes AWT taskbar attention, while completely omitting the sprite API unification and window query methods. Candidate B correctly removes tray icons, adds all three window state queries, and unifies sprite loading via addSpritesheetAndAnimation, but loses the anchorClipName overload and misses the FlixelGame.destroy() tray-cleanup required by the acceptance criteria."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 85,
  "candidate_b_score": 78,
  "rationale": "Both candidates correctly export applySelectionToChart, move useElementSize before the dependent effect, and add width/height to the effect dependencies to fix stale selection on resize. Candidate A preserves the original detailed comment explaining the URL round-trip and uPlot ready hook complement, which aligns better with the reference's intent to retain explanatory context. Candidate B oversimplifies the comment into a single line, losing important maintainer context. Neither candidate includes the reference's test file, so both are marked down on completeness, but A's minimal, documentation-preserving churn gives it the edge."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 78,
  "candidate_b_score": 52,
  "rationale": "Candidate A implements a fully functional local knowledge base in the API route with keyword matching and fallback handling, adds a polished canvas audio visualizer with device-pixel-ratio support and configurable sizing, and integrates typewriter effects with typing-state management in the chat panel. It deviates from the reference by bypassing the API route in the hook (redundant logic) and lacks per-character scroll callbacks (only scrolling on message add/completion). Candidate B is weaker: its API route is a non-functional stub returning a placeholder string, the visualizer is hardcoded and lacks configurability, and the typewriter integration only scrolls on completion rather than as characters appear. Both candidates miss the per-character onUpdate scrolling from the reference, but Candidate A is substantially more complete and aligned overall."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 85,
  "candidate_b_score": 60,
  "rationale": "Candidate A correctly implements all required features—local rule-based API fallback, canvas audio visualizer, and typewriter message streaming—with only minor deviations (generic 'Sir' references and a small extra GET endpoint). Candidate B fundamentally misidentifies the developer as 'Anthony Stark' and supplies fictional contact details, a major content and alignment error. Candidate B also retains legacy UI remnants and its TypewriterText restarts from '' whenever parent callbacks change, creating a noticeable functional bug."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 95,
  "candidate_b_score": 85,
  "rationale": "Candidate A closely matches the reference structure (single inline ordenarItens, local comparison counters, no extra post-sort listing) and satisfies all task requirements with minimal unrelated churn. Candidate B is functionally correct and complete, but deviates more by adding an unused enum, a global comparison counter, extra modular sort functions, automatic listing after each sort, and a cancel option not present in the reference, reducing alignment."
}

{
  "winner": "candidate_a",
  "candidate_a_score": 70,
  "candidate_b_score": 20,
  "rationale": "Candidate A modifies the correct target file (run-review-client.tsx) and implements the core requirements: sin_match bulk actions with confirmation, a search modal for manual linking, the Equipo column, green 'Crear nueva' badges, and notas_revisor tracking in resolverBulk. However, it misses the required dropdown menu for row actions (using individual icon buttons instead) and uses manual overlay divs rather than the project's Dialog/AlertDialog primitives. Candidate B works on an entirely different route and data model (revisar-sync-client.tsx / padron_sync_diffs), making it fundamentally misaligned with the reference direction and task scope, despite using proper UI components."
}

 {
  "winner": "candidate_a",
